<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910118-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>910118-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   Grumman's Myers   Is Named President,   Chief of Operations</HL><DATE>01/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B12</SO><CO>   GQ WNEWS</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   BETHPAGE, N.Y. -- Grumman Corp. said that Robert J. Myers,56 years old, was elected president, chief operating officerand a director of the aerospace, electronic systems andinformation services concern.   Mr. Myers, former president of the Grumman Data Systemsdivision, succeeds Renso L. Caporali, 57, who remainschairman and chief executive officer of the parent company.The post of chief operating officer had been vacant.</LP><TEXT>   Grumman's executive ranks have been shaken in recentmonths by the resignations of Thomas A. Guarino as presidentof the company's military electronics group and of JohnO'Brien, Mr. Caporali's predecessor. News reports in Decemberalleged that the men were involved in defense-procurementfraud. Mr. Guarino has said he is innocent of any wrongdoing.When he resigned in July, Mr. O'Brien said he left forpersonal reasons.   Mr. Myers has held various administrative posts at Grummansince joining the company in 1957. The division he has headedsince 1986 provides computer services to all Grumman units aswell as to federal government agencies and small businesses.   Gerald H. Sandler, 56, senior vice president, informationsystems, of the data systems division, succeeds Mr. Myers asdivision president. Thomas J. Kane Jr., 57, senior vicepresident, business development, for the Grumman AircraftSystems division, was elected to the same post with theparent.</TEXT></DOC>